one":null,"comments":3,"created_at":"2021-06-13T22:55:03Z","updated_at":"2022-02-25T16:42:37Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"COLLABORATOR","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"Update: @RNKuhns has offboarded.\r\n\r\nWe´re also currently building probabilistic metrics, and we should ensure that the point prediction metrics are interface compatible (e.g., loss samples). I will look into this and take over @RNKuhns´ PRs.\r\n---\r\n\r\nFor our future roadmap to include advanced benchmarking and testing capabilities, I think forecasting metrics will need to be able to return metrics of losses (in case the metric is some average).\r\n\r\nFor example, the commonly used Diebold-Mariano test to compare predictions losses of two predictions vs ground truth requires losses by forecast time point, not just an average.\r\n\r\nThis is perhaps easier to attach to the class version of the metrics (as a method) than to the function version?\r\n\r\nWould be interested to hear your thoughts, @RNKuhns, @mloning, @aiwalter.\r\n\r\nAs a side point, not all metrics will have this, but they could return jackknife pseudo-samples by default, which would more easily give access to algorithms like jackknife and jackknife-plus estimates.","closed_by":null,"reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sktime/sktime/issues/958/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sktime/sktime/issues/958/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null}